All five files are written. Here's what was produced:

---

**`.lathe/goal.md`** — The customer champion's behavioral doc. Five richly-described stakeholders (Self-Hoster, Platform Developer, Chart Author, Security Auditor, Delivery Machine), each with concrete first-encounter journeys the champion walks each cycle, an emotional signal to track, and success/failure conditions. Tensions are grounded in real code (the `ha_exception` pattern, the bootstrap seam, the `contract/validate.py` vs. claimed autarky gap). The two-source ranking model: floor (constitutional gates) first, lived experience second. No layer ladder.

**`.lathe/skills/journeys.md`** — Concrete command-by-command first-encounter journeys for all five stakeholders, with annotations of where friction shows up. The champion runs these each cycle.

**`.lathe/skills/architecture.md`** — Key decisions: App-of-Apps, chart locations, HA invariants, autarky enforcement points, cluster contract, delivery machine structure.

**`.lathe/skills/testing.md`** — How this project tests: constitutional gates, Helm chart gates, shell gates, CI workflows, kind integration tests, YAML validation.

**`.lathe/skills/domains.md`** — Domain boundary map: Kubernetes/Helm, GitOps/ArgoCD, Zero Trust/Istio, Sovereignty/Autarky, Constitutional Gates, Sprint/Ceremony System, Shell Scripting, Observability. Includes a boundary confusion matrix for the most common misattributions.

**`.lathe/alignment-summary.md`** — Human-readable summary: who each stakeholder is (one line), emotional signal per stakeholder, three real tensions with tie-breaking signals, security assessment (workflows use `pull_request`, not `pull_request_target` — safe; repo is public; branch protection unverified from code), and uncertainties (bootstrap VPS scripts not confirmed present, G9 may be failing 20 charts, S2 journey requires a running cluster to walk fully).
